Abstract As single-modality models advance, multimodal learning systems are becoming critical for real-world deployments. However, their efficacy is consistently hindered by varying modality quality and reliability. Existing methods relying on uniform weighting or static correlation estimation fail to capture this dynamic landscape, leading to over-reliance on unreliable sources. We propose the Adaptive Uncertainty-Aware Fusion (AUAF) framework, which jointly models Uncertainty Quantification (UQ) via Monte Carlo dropout and Cross-modal Consistency (CC) via latent-space cosine similarity. This enables principled, dynamic down-weighting of unreliable modalities. AUAF's decoupled architecture supports dual deployment: as a plug-and-play module or a fully integrated component within existing frameworks. Experiments on NLVR2 and selected portions of VQA v2.0 demonstrate that AUAF achieves superior performance and robustness compared to uniform weighting or correlation-based baselines, particularly with noisy or incomplete modalities.